67–1131","about 1060":"about 1060","1066":"1066","1044":"1044","1120":"1120","1131":"1131","1097":"1097","1086":"1086","1064":"1064","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","Cir 1064":"1064","1060":"1060","1059":"1059","1125":"1125","Abt 1067":"about 1067","1067":"1067","Ilkeston, Derbyshire, England":"Ilkeston, Derbyshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Muskham, Nottinghamshire, England":"North Muskham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Normandy, Plouigneau, Brittany, France":"Plouigneau, Brittany, France","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, , England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Herrera","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Luis, Jorge, Francisco, Raul, Rafael, Mario, Roberto.","Spanish: habitational name from any of various places in the provinces of Seville and Badajoz named Herrera, from a word meaning ‘iron smithy, blacksmith's forge’ (a derivative of <i>hierro</i> ‘iron’, Latin <i>ferrum</i>). In the US, it is also found among Native Americans (Pueblos) in NM. Compare   De Herrera   and   Errera  .","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the name their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"De Herrera","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alfonso, Juan, Carlos, Frutoso, Jose, Manuel, Orlando, Alcario, Andres, Angel, Eloisa, Ernesto.","Spanish: habitational name, formed with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, for someone from any of various places called Herrera (see   Herrera  )."]},{"name":"Errera","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish   Herrera  ."]}]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":26,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":46,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":56,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Beatrice Herrera was born in 1040, in Nottingham, Nottingha